<subSubSection id="FD1F40EAAC7F35C00D793F1ED1898F28" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" type="general">
<paragraph id="C2D6486494B513D5CD07652CB8B9B447" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">General</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E5D6B5B9CFD694E7AEB39874892746BE" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">
<taxonomicName id="0EDE642A8C5A42202EC373BCBF3D75E8" authorityName="Barboza" authorityYear="2011" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Solanaceae" genus="Capsicum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="eximium">Capsicum eximium</taxonomicName>
var. 
<emphasis id="603CFE853B2EB67432FDD2A61D1B2998" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">tomentosum</emphasis>
was described as an unusual glandular tomentose variety of 
<taxonomicName id="64BF8BD5B7B8395C16291543276FB39B" authorityName="Barboza" authorityYear="2011" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Solanaceae" genus="Capsicum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="eximium">Capsicum eximium</taxonomicName>
Hunz. The presence of this kind of pubescence densely covering the vegetative organs, pedicels, and calyx, and of a 5-10 toothed-calyx (
<figureCitation id="BBF7DF465FFD324338181CBD2F7AB394" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Capsicum eshbaughii. A embryo B, H, F, J, L glandular trichomes C fruit D non-glandular trichome E flowering branch G flower I gynoecium K seed M open corolla N fruiting calyx. Line drawing by P. Peralta; voucher A, C, K, N Nee 36164; B, D-J, L, M Eshbaugh 1943 b." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/9860" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">Fig. 2 N</figureCitation>
) in specimens from a restricted area in south-central Bolivia (Dpto. Santa Cruz and Cochabamba) makes them quite different from 
<taxonomicName id="B44AF7AF6FAAFD3C97C10C28672F6560" authorityName="Barboza" authorityYear="2011" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Solanaceae" genus="Capsicum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="eximium">Capsicum eximium</taxonomicName>
. In fact, 
<taxonomicName id="DF6FA2A6C6EC62D55D4C53EE76889F8A" authorityName="Barboza" authorityYear="2011" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Solanaceae" genus="Capsicum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="eximium">Capsicum eximium</taxonomicName>
has non- glandular pubescence (
<figureCitation id="D267A61BA4779635620F318A0B713C7C" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Capsicum eximium. A, J anthers in ventral and dorsal view respectively B flowering branch C flower D, G transverse section of the seed coat E fruit F embryo H gynoecium I seed K open corolla L seed in cross section M non-glandular trichome. Line drawing by N. Flury; voucher A, C-M: Hunziker 1907; B, Hunziker 7346." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/9861" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">Fig. 3 M</figureCitation>
), a calyx with only 5 teeth (
<figureCitation id="ADFF4AC1C02B25C3B4E3986DE7F6866A" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Capsicum eximium. A, J anthers in ventral and dorsal view respectively B flowering branch C flower D, G transverse section of the seed coat E fruit F embryo H gynoecium I seed K open corolla L seed in cross section M non-glandular trichome. Line drawing by N. Flury; voucher A, C-M: Hunziker 1907; B, Hunziker 7346." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/9861" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">Fig. 3 C, E</figureCitation>
), and is distributed in a larger area (Bolivia: La Paz to Tarija and Argentina: Jujuy to 
<normalizedToken id="6EAFE4682A748ADA4E4A44DB42AB75A5" originalValue="Tucumán">Tucuman</normalizedToken>
).
</paragraph>
