<paragraph id="CB5DC3D819832D921F4643AAB3176D8F" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">
Glandular hairs are rare in 
<taxonomicName id="16AAC35DFE4D754B4F0669295ADA7A42" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Solanaceae" genus="Capsicum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">Capsicum</taxonomicName>
. The dense indumentum of 
<taxonomicName id="A1CCC9A9F80D9196EFFDA8FD9678B111" authorityName="Barboza" authorityYear="2011" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Solanaceae" genus="Capsicum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="eshbaughii">Capsicum eshbaughii</taxonomicName>
consists of different types of glandular trichomes, some of them observed only in this species. The hair variations are: long simple hairs with multicellular and verrucate stalks and unicellular stipitate (
<figureCitation id="310B4223843CB5FAFEE8F940B1B1BA21" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Capsicum eshbaughii. A embryo B, H, F, J, L glandular trichomes C fruit D non-glandular trichome E flowering branch G flower I gynoecium K seed M open corolla N fruiting calyx. Line drawing by P. Peralta; voucher A, C, K, N Nee 36164; B, D-J, L, M Eshbaugh 1943 b." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/9860" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">Fig. 2 F</figureCitation>
) or not stipitate (
<figureCitation id="2B69E978781F104EADF3CB3DB5EBEFA1" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Capsicum eshbaughii. A embryo B, H, F, J, L glandular trichomes C fruit D non-glandular trichome E flowering branch G flower I gynoecium K seed M open corolla N fruiting calyx. Line drawing by P. Peralta; voucher A, C, K, N Nee 36164; B, D-J, L, M Eshbaugh 1943 b." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/9860" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">Fig. 2 B</figureCitation>
) heads; short hairs with bicellular smooth stalks and multicellular heads (
<figureCitation id="700B8B727A11221633DC9A407DB0CB37" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Capsicum eshbaughii. A embryo B, H, F, J, L glandular trichomes C fruit D non-glandular trichome E flowering branch G flower I gynoecium K seed M open corolla N fruiting calyx. Line drawing by P. Peralta; voucher A, C, K, N Nee 36164; B, D-J, L, M Eshbaugh 1943 b." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/9860" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">Fig. 2 J</figureCitation>
); and bifurcate hairs with both branches ending in a unicellular head (
<figureCitation id="4DCC7096E4337997016E38F713AB6DCC" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Capsicum eshbaughii. A embryo B, H, F, J, L glandular trichomes C fruit D non-glandular trichome E flowering branch G flower I gynoecium K seed M open corolla N fruiting calyx. Line drawing by P. Peralta; voucher A, C, K, N Nee 36164; B, D-J, L, M Eshbaugh 1943 b." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/9860" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">Fig. 2 L</figureCitation>
) or one branch non-glandular and the other longer and glandular (
<figureCitation id="976589F63D50254E4CE20A94540B6BF9" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Capsicum eshbaughii. A embryo B, H, F, J, L glandular trichomes C fruit D non-glandular trichome E flowering branch G flower I gynoecium K seed M open corolla N fruiting calyx. Line drawing by P. Peralta; voucher A, C, K, N Nee 36164; B, D-J, L, M Eshbaugh 1943 b." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/9860" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">Fig. 2 H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EAD8F11E8AEE359282F7101F01705687" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">
<taxonomicName id="A71E81145DC8818395D9959DC0BD2BCC" authorityName="Barboza" authorityYear="2011" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Solanaceae" genus="Capsicum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="eshbaughii">Capsicum eshbaughii</taxonomicName>
, together with 
<taxonomicName id="B73824C0A048ADA9522155F5B97CFBC9" authorityName="Barboza" authorityYear="2011" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Solanaceae" genus="Capsicum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="eximium">Capsicum eximium</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4E25F63BDCA623CEDA881FBFEAAA8E57" authorityName="C. B. Heiser &amp; P. G. Smith" authorityYear="1958" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Solanaceae" genus="Capsicum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Tubiflorae" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="cardenasii">Capsicum cardenasii</taxonomicName>
Heiser &amp; P.G.Sm., is known as 
<normalizedToken id="0A993FB2445CA6D14A88EB23944F1F0C" originalValue="“ulupica”">&quot;ulupica&quot;</normalizedToken>
(Eshbaugh 1943 C); their very pungent fruits are very much appreciated as a spice or as pickles in the kitchens of Bolivia (
<bibRefCitation id="EB6371D6E6CC44EF2B1660689E14C7CD" author="Eshbaugh, WH" journalOrPublisher="Baileya" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" pagination="13 - 16" refId="B17" refString="Eshbaugh, WH, Smith, PG, 1971. A new variety of chili pepper, Capsicum eximium var. tomentosum (Solanaceae). Baileya 18: 13 - 16" title="A new variety of chili pepper, Capsicum eximium var. tomentosum (Solanaceae)." volume="18" year="1971">Eshbaugh and Smith 1971</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="83F4CEE794299F6E0CEB7E55C6A7DDE5" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">This species is named in honor to Dr. W.H. Eshbaugh (Miami University) who first recognised the distinctness of this species and devoted part of his research to the taxonomy of chili peppers.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="781C079972025CC733E595E880542BD5" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">
<taxonomicName id="123B385A39006B7A57C300A05A6699D6" genus="Specimens" lsidName="" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Examined">Specimens Examined</taxonomicName>
